07/11/2010
BUCHAREST, Romania -- A mass grave containing the remains of Jews killed by the Romanian army in 1941 has been found in the northeast, media reported on Friday (November 5th). The Elie Wiesel National Institute says experts have discovered 16 bodies so far, with more expected. The institute believes the grave could contain up to 100 bodies of men, women and children. The grave is located in the Vulturi forest in Propricani, northeast of Bucharest. First reports about the Holocaust-era mass grave appeared in 2002. A 2004 report concluded that 280,000 Jews and 11,000 Roma were killed under Ion Antonescu's regime during World War II. (CNN, AFP, BBC, AP - 05/11/10)
